# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: freebsd-os
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] The **Berkeley Software Distribution** (**BSD**), also known as **Berkeley Unix**, is a discontinued Unix operating system developed and distributed by the Computer Systems Research Group (CSRG) at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] First released in 1978, it began as an improved derivative of AT&T's original Unix developed at Bell Labs, based on the source code.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Over time, BSD evolved into a distinct operating system and played a significant role in computing and the development and dissemination of Unix-like systems.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] BSD development was initially led by Bill Joy, who together with Ozalp Babaoglu added virtual memory capability to Unix running on a VAX-11 computer.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] During the 1980s, BSD gained widespread adoption by workstation vendors in the form of proprietary Unix distributions—such as DEC with Ultrix and Sun Microsystems with SunOS—due to its permissive licensing and familiarity among engineers.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] BSD also became the most widely used Unix variant in academic institutions, where it was used for the study of operating systems.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] The BSD project received funding from DARPA until 1988, during which time BSD incorporated ARPANET support and later implemented the TCP/IP protocol suite, released as part of BSD NET/1 in 1988.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] By that time, the codebase had diverged significantly from the original AT&T Unix, with estimates suggesting that less than 5% of the code remained from AT&T.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] As a result, NET/1 was distributed without requiring an AT&T source license.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Berkeley ended its Unix research in 1992, following reduced funding and complications arising from the Unix copyright lawsuit.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] As the original BSD became obsolete, the term "BSD" came to refer primarily to its open-source descendants, including FreeBSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD, and DragonFly BSD, and derivatives of those projects, such as TrueOS.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] BSD-derived code, along with Mach code, also formed the basis for Darwin; that, in turn, has been incorporated into Apple's proprietary operating systems, such as macOS and iOS.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Windows NT 3.1's networking stack used a BSD-derived TCP/IP implementation, and some BSD-based networking utilities for that stack are also provided with Windows NT.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Code from BSD's open descendants have themselves also been integrated into various modern platforms, including the system software for the PlayStation 5 and other embedded or commercial devices.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] The earliest distributions of Unix from Bell Labs in the 1970s included the source code to the operating system, allowing researchers at universities to modify and extend Unix.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] The operating system arrived at Berkeley in 1974, at the request of computer science professor Bob Fabry who had been on the program committee for the Symposium on Operating Systems Principles where Unix was first presented.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] A PDP-11/45 was bought to run the system, but for budgetary reasons, this machine was shared with the mathematics and statistics groups at Berkeley, who used RSTS, so that Unix only ran on the machine eight hours per day (sometimes during the day, sometimes during the night).
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] A larger PDP-11/70 was installed at Berkeley the following year, using money from the Ingres database project.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] BSD began life as a variant of Unix that programmers at the University of California at Berkeley, initially led by Bill Joy, began developing in the late 1970s.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] It included extra features, which were intertwined with code owned by AT&T.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] In 1975, Ken Thompson took a sabbatical from Bell Labs and came to Berkeley as a visiting professor.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] He helped to install Version 6 Unix and started working on a Pascal implementation for the system.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Graduate students Chuck Haley and Bill Joy improved Thompson's Pascal and implemented an improved text editor, ex.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Other universities became interested in the software at Berkeley, and so in 1977 Joy started compiling the first Berkeley Software Distribution (1BSD), which was released on March 9, 1978.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] 1BSD was an add-on to Version 6 Unix rather than a complete operating system in its own right.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] The second Berkeley Software Distribution (2BSD), released in May 1979, included updated versions of the 1BSD software as well as two new programs by Joy that persist on Unix systems to this day: the vi text editor (a visual version of ex) and the C shell.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Some 75 copies of 2BSD were sent out by Bill Joy.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] A VAX computer was installed at Berkeley in 1978, but the port of Unix to the VAX architecture, UNIX/32V, did not take advantage of the VAX's virtual memory capabilities.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] The kernel of 32V was largely rewritten to include Berkeley graduate student Özalp Babaoğlu's virtual memory implementation, and a complete operating system including the new kernel, ports of the 2BSD utilities to the VAX, and the utilities from 32V was released as 3BSD at the end of 1979.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] 3BSD was also alternatively called Virtual VAX/UNIX or VMUNIX (for Virtual Memory Unix), and BSD kernel images were normally called `/vmunix` until 4.4BSD.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] After 4.3BSD was released in June 1986, it was determined that BSD would move away from the aging VAX platform.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] The Power 6/32 platform (codenamed "Tahoe") developed by Computer Consoles Inc. seemed promising at the time, but was abandoned by its developers shortly thereafter.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Nonetheless, the **4.3BSD-Tahoe** port (June 1988) proved valuable, as it led to a separation of machine-dependent and machine-independent code in BSD which would improve the system's future portability.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] In addition to portability, the CSRG worked on an implementation of the OSI network protocol stack, improvements to the kernel virtual memory system and (with Van Jacobson of LBL) new TCP/IP algorithms to accommodate the growth of the Internet.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Until then, all versions of BSD used proprietary AT&T Unix code, and were therefore subject to an AT&T software license.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Source code licenses had become very expensive and several outside parties had expressed interest in a separate release of the networking code, which had been developed entirely outside AT&T and would not be subject to the licensing requirement.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] This led to **Networking Release 1** (**Net/1**), which was made available to non-licensees of AT&T code and was freely redistributable under the terms of the BSD license.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] After Net/1, BSD developer Keith Bostic proposed that more non-AT&T sections of the BSD system be released under the same license as Net/1.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] To this end, he started a project to reimplement most of the standard Unix utilities without using the AT&T code.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Within eighteen months, all of the AT&T utilities had been replaced, and it was determined that only a few AT&T files remained in the kernel.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] These files were removed, and the result was the June 1991 release of Networking Release 2 (Net/2), a nearly complete operating system that was freely distributable.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Net/2 was the basis for two separate ports of BSD to the Intel 80386 architecture: the free 386BSD by William and Lynne Jolitz, and the proprietary BSD/386 (later renamed BSD/OS) by Berkeley Software Design (BSDi).
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] 386BSD itself was short-lived, but became the initial code base of the NetBSD and FreeBSD projects that were started shortly thereafter.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] BSDi soon found itself in legal trouble with AT&T's Unix System Laboratories (USL) subsidiary, then the owners of the System V copyright and the Unix trademark.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] BSDi* lawsuit was filed in 1992 and led to an injunction on the distribution of Net/2 until the validity of USL's copyright claims on the source could be determined.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] The lawsuit slowed development of the free-software descendants of BSD for nearly two years while their legal status was in question, and as a result systems based on the Linux kernel, which did not have such legal ambiguity, gained greater support.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] The lawsuit was settled in January 1994, largely in Berkeley's favor.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Of the 18,000 files in the Berkeley distribution, only three had to be removed and 70 modified to show USL copyright notices.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] A further condition of the settlement was that USL would not file further lawsuits against users and distributors of the Berkeley-owned code in the upcoming 4.4BSD release.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] The final release from Berkeley was 1995's **4.4BSD-Lite Release 2**, after which the CSRG was dissolved and development of BSD at Berkeley ceased.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Since then, several variants based directly or indirectly on 4.4BSD-Lite (such as FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD and DragonFly BSD) have been maintained.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] The permissive nature of the BSD license has allowed many other operating systems, both open-source and proprietary, to incorporate BSD source code.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] For example, Windows NT 3.1 used BSD code in its implementation of TCP/IP and bundles recompiled versions of BSD's command-line networking tools since Windows 2000.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Darwin, the basis for Apple's macOS and iOS, is based on 4.4BSD-Lite2 and FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Various commercial Unix operating systems, such as Solaris, also incorporate BSD code.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Starting with the 8th Edition, versions of Research Unix at Bell Labs had a close relationship to BSD.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] This began when 4.1cBSD for the VAX was used as the basis for Research Unix 8th Edition.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] This continued in subsequent versions, such as the 9th Edition, which incorporated source code and improvements from 4.3BSD.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] The result was that these later versions of Research Unix were closer to BSD than they were to System V.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Curry wrote about the differences between BSD and System V.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Berkeley's Unix was the first Unix to include libraries supporting the Internet Protocol stacks: *Berkeley sockets*.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] A Unix implementation of IP's predecessor, the ARPAnet's NCP, with FTP and Telnet clients, had been produced at the University of Illinois in 1975, and was available at Berkeley.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] However, the memory scarcity on the PDP-11 forced a complicated design and performance problems.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] By integrating sockets with the Unix operating system's file descriptors, it became almost as easy to read and write data across a network as it was to access a disk.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] The AT&T laboratory eventually released their own STREAMS library, which incorporated much of the same functionality in a software stack with a different architecture, but the wide distribution of the existing sockets library reduced the impact of the new API.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Early versions of BSD were used to form Sun Microsystems' SunOS, founding the first wave of popular Unix workstations.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Some BSD operating systems can run native software of several other operating systems on the same architecture, using a binary compatibility layer.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] This is much simpler and faster than emulation; for example, it allows applications intended for Linux to be run at effectively full speed.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] This makes BSDs not only suitable for server environments, but also for workstation ones, given the increasing availability of commercial or closed-source software for Linux only.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] This also allows administrators to migrate legacy commercial applications, which may have only supported commercial Unix variants, to a more modern operating system, retaining the functionality of such applications until they can be replaced by a better alternative.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Current BSD operating system variants support many of the common IEEE, ANSI, ISO, and POSIX standards, while retaining most of the traditional BSD behavior.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Like AT&T Unix, the BSD kernel is monolithic, meaning that device drivers in the kernel run in privileged mode, as part of the core of the operating system.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Several operating systems are based on BSD, including FreeBSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD, DragonFly BSD, MidnightBSD, MirOS BSD, GhostBSD, and Darwin.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] Both NetBSD and FreeBSD were created in 1993.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] They were initially derived from 386BSD (also known as "Jolix"), and merged the 4.4BSD-Lite source code in 1994.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] OpenBSD was forked from NetBSD in 1995, and DragonFly BSD was forked from FreeBSD in 2003.
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] BSD was also used as the basis for several proprietary versions of Unix, such as Sun's SunOS, Sequent's DYNIX, NeXT's NeXTSTEP, DEC's Ultrix and OSF/1 AXP (now Tru64 UNIX).
[src:freebsd-os/berkeley-software-distribution] NeXTSTEP later became the foundation for Apple Inc.'s macOS.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] DTrace can be used to get a global overview of a running system, such as the amount of memory, CPU time, filesystem and network resources used by the active processes.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] It can also provide much more fine-grained information, such as a log of the arguments with which a specific function is being called, or a list of the processes accessing a specific file.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] In 2010, Oracle Corporation acquired Sun Microsystems and announced the discontinuation of OpenSolaris.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] As a community effort of some core Solaris engineers to create a truly open source Solaris, illumos operating system was announced via webinar on Thursday, 3 August 2010, as a fork on OpenSolaris OS/Net consolidation, including DTrace technology.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] In October 2011, Oracle announced the porting of DTrace to Linux, and in 2019 official DTrace for Fedora is available on GitHub.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] For several years an unofficial DTrace port to Linux was available, with no changes in licensing terms.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] In August 2017, Oracle released DTrace kernel code under the GPLv2+ license, and user space code under GPLv2 and UPL licensing.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] In September 2018 Microsoft announced that they had ported DTrace from FreeBSD to Windows.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] In September 2016 the OpenDTrace effort began on GitHub with both code and comprehensive documentation of the system's internals.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] The OpenDTrace effort maintains the original CDDL licensing for the code from OpenSolaris with additional code contributions coming under a BSD 2 Clause license.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] The goal of OpenDTrace is to provide an OS agnostic, portable implementation of DTrace that is acceptable to all consumers, including macOS, FreeBSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD, and Linux as well as embedded systems.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Sun Microsystems designed DTrace to give operational insights that allow users to tune and troubleshoot applications and the OS itself.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Testers write tracing programs (also referred to as scripts) using the D programming language (not to be confused with other programming languages named "D").
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] The language, inspired by C, includes added functions and variables specific to tracing.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] D programs resemble AWK programs in structure; they consist of a list of one or more *probes* (instrumentation points), and each probe is associated with an action.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] These probes are comparable to a pointcut in aspect-oriented programming.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Whenever the condition for the probe is met, the associated action is executed (the probe "fires").
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] A typical probe might fire when a certain file is opened, or a process is started, or a certain line of code is executed.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] A probe that fires may analyze the run-time situation by accessing the call stack and context variables and evaluating expressions; it can then print out or log some information, record it in a database, or modify context variables.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] The reading and writing of context variables allows probes to pass information to each other, allowing them to cooperatively analyze the correlation of different events.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Special consideration has been taken to make DTrace safe to use in a production environment.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] For example, there is minimal probe effect when tracing is underway, and no performance impact associated with any disabled probe; this is important since there are tens of thousands of DTrace probes that can be enabled.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] New probes can also be created dynamically.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] DTrace scripts can be invoked directly from the command line, providing one or more probes and actions as arguments.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Scripts can also be written which can reach hundreds of lines in length, although typically only tens of lines are needed for advanced troubleshooting and analysis.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Over 200 examples of open source DTrace scripts can be found in the DTraceToolkit, created by Brendan Gregg (author of the DTrace book), which also provides documentation and demonstrations of each.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] DTrace first became available for use in November 2003, and was formally released as part of Sun's Solaris 10 in January 2005.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] DTrace was the first component of the OpenSolaris project to have its source code released under the Common Development and Distribution License (CDDL).
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] DTrace is an integral part of illumos and related distributions.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] DTrace is a standard part of FreeBSD and NetBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Apple added DTrace support in Mac OS X 10.5 "Leopard", including a GUI called Instruments.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Over 40 DTrace scripts from the DTraceToolkit are included in /usr/bin, including tools to examine disk I/O (iosnoop) and process execution (execsnoop).
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Unlike other platforms that DTrace is supported on, Mac OS X has a flag (P_LNOATTACH) that a program may set that disallows tracing of that process by debugging utilities such as DTrace and gdb.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] In the original Mac OS X DTrace implementation, this could affect tracing of other system information, as unrelated probes that should fire while a program with this flag set was running would fail to do so.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] The OS X 10.5.3 update addressed this issue a few months later.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] However, since El Capitan, System Integrity Protection prevents user from DTracing protected binary by default.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] The Linux port of DTrace has been available since 2008; work continues actively to enhance and fix issues.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] There is also an active implementation on github.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Standard core providers are available (fbt, syscall, profile), plus a special "instr" provider (some of the Solaris providers are not yet available as of 2013).
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] The Linux DTrace implementation is a loadable kernel module, which means that the kernel itself requires no modification, and thus allows DTrace to avoid CDDL vs.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] GPL licensing conflicts (in its source form, at least).
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] However, once DTrace is loaded the kernel instance will be marked as tainted.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] In 2007, a developer at QNX Software Systems announced on his blog that he and a colleague were working on incorporating DTrace into the QNX operating system.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Oracle Corporation added beta DTrace support for Oracle Linux in 2011, as a technology preview in the Unbreakable Enterprise Kernel release 2, which is under GPLv2 (the DTrace Linux kernel module was originally released under CDDL).
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] General availability was announced in December 2012.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] On March 11, 2019, Microsoft released a version of DTrace for Windows 10 insider builds.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Microsoft included DTrace as a built-in tool in Windows Server 2025.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] With a supported *language provider*, DTrace can retrieve context of the code, including function, source file, and line number location.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Further, dynamic memory allocation and garbage collection can be made available if supported by the language.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] Supported language providers include assembly language, C, C++, Java, Erlang, JavaScript, Perl, PHP, Python, Ruby, shell script, and Tcl.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] DTrace was designed and implemented by Bryan Cantrill, Mike Shapiro, and Adam Leventhal.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] The authors received recognition in 2005 for the innovations in DTrace from *InfoWorld* and *Technology Review*.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] DTrace won the top prize in *The Wall Street Journal*'s 2006 Technology Innovation Awards competition.
[src:freebsd-os/dtrace] The authors were recognized by USENIX with the Software Tools User Group (STUG) award in 2008.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD maintains a complete system, delivering a kernel, device drivers, userland utilities, and documentation, as opposed to Linux only delivering a kernel and drivers, and relying on third-parties such as GNU for system software.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The FreeBSD source code is generally released under a permissive BSD license, as opposed to the copyleft GPL used by Linux.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The project includes a security team overseeing all software shipped in the base distribution.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Third-party applications may be installed using the pkg package management system or from source via FreeBSD Ports.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The project is supported and promoted by the FreeBSD Foundation.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD contains a large amount of code from OpenBSD and other current BSD systems.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In 1974, Professor Bob Fabry of the University of California, Berkeley, acquired a Unix source license from AT&T.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Supported by funding from DARPA, the Computer Systems Research Group started to modify and improve AT&T Research Unix.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The group called this modified version "Berkeley Unix" or "Berkeley Software Distribution" (BSD), implementing features such as TCP/IP, virtual memory, and the Berkeley Fast File System.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The BSD project was founded in 1976 by Bill Joy.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] But since BSD contained code from AT&T Unix, all recipients had to first get a license from AT&T in order to use BSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In June 1989, "Networking Release 1" or simply Net-1 – the first public version of BSD – was released.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] After releasing Net-1, Keith Bostic, a developer of BSD, suggested replacing all AT&T code with freely-redistributable code under the original BSD license.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Work on replacing AT&T code began and, after 18 months, much of the AT&T code was replaced.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] However, six files containing AT&T code remained in the kernel.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The BSD developers decided to release the "Networking Release 2" (Net-2) without those six files.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In 1992, several months after the release of Net-2, William and Lynne Jolitz wrote replacements for the six AT&T files, ported BSD to Intel 80386-based microprocessors, and called their new operating system 386BSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] They released 386BSD via an anonymous FTP server.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The development flow of 386BSD was slow, and after a period of neglect, a group of 386BSD users including Nate Williams, Rod Grimes and Jordan Hubbard decided to branch out on their own so that they could keep the operating system up to date.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] On 19 June 1993, the name FreeBSD was chosen for the project.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The first version of FreeBSD was released in November 1993.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In the early days of the project's inception, a company named Walnut Creek CDROM, upon the suggestion of the two FreeBSD developers, agreed to release the operating system on CD-ROM.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In addition to that, the company employed Jordan Hubbard and David Greenman, ran FreeBSD on its servers, sponsored FreeBSD conferences and published FreeBSD-related books, including *The Complete FreeBSD* by Greg Lehey.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] By 1997, FreeBSD was Walnut Creek's "most successful product".
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The company later renamed itself to *The FreeBSD Mall* and later iXsystems.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] 386BSD and FreeBSD were both derived from BSD releases.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In January 1992, Berkeley Software Design Inc.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] (BSDi) started to release BSD/386, later called BSD/OS, an operating system similar to FreeBSD and based on 4.3BSD Net/2.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] AT&T filed a lawsuit against BSDi and alleged distribution of AT&T source code in violation of license agreements.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The lawsuit was settled out of court and the exact terms were not all disclosed.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The only one that became public was that BSDi would migrate its source base to the newer 4.4BSD-Lite2 sources.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Although not involved in the litigation, it was suggested to FreeBSD that it should also move to 4.4BSD-Lite2.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD 2.0, which was released in November 1994, was the first version of FreeBSD without any code from AT&T.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Today, FreeBSD is used by many IT companies such as IBM, Nokia, Juniper Networks, and NetApp to build their products.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Certain parts of Apple's macOS operating system are based on FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Both the PlayStation 3 and Nintendo Switch operating system also borrow certain components from FreeBSD, while the PlayStation 4 operating system is derived from FreeBSD 9.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Netflix, WhatsApp, and FlightAware are also examples of large, successful and heavily network-oriented companies which are running FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD contains a significant collection of server-related software in the base system and the ports collection, allowing FreeBSD to be configured and used as a mail server, web server, firewall, FTP server, DNS server and a router, among other applications.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD can be installed on a regular desktop or a laptop.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The X Window System is not installed by default, but is available in the FreeBSD ports collection.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] A number of desktop environments such as Lumina, GNOME, KDE, and Xfce, as well as lightweight window managers such as Openbox, Fluxbox, dwm, and bspwm, are also available for FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Major web browsers such as Firefox and Chromium are available unofficially on FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] As of FreeBSD 12, support for a modern graphics stack is available via drm-kmod.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] A large number of wireless adapters are supported.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD releases installation images for supported platforms.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Since FreeBSD 13 the focus has been on x86-64 and AArch64 platforms which have Tier 1 support, and 32-bit platforms no longer have Tier 1 support.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] IA-32 is a Tier 2 platform in FreeBSD 13 and 14 (but will be dropped in next version).
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] 32-bit ARM processors using armv6 or armv7 also have Tier 2 support, and ARMv7 will keep support.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] 64-bit versions of RISC-V and PowerPC (that still has 32-bit tier 2 supported, but will be dropped in next version) are also supported.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Interest in the RISC-V architecture has been growing.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The MIPS architecture port was marked for deprecation and there is no image for current 13.4 or later available.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD's TCP/IP stack is based on the 4.2BSD implementation of TCP/IP which greatly contributed to the widespread adoption of these protocols.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD also supports IPv6, SCTP, IPSec, and wireless networking (Wi-Fi).
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The IPv6 and IPSec stacks were taken from the KAME project.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Prior to version 11.0, FreeBSD supported IPX and AppleTalk protocols, but they are considered obsolescent and have been dropped.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] As of FreeBSD 5.4, support for the Common Address Redundancy Protocol (CARP) was imported from the OpenBSD project.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] CARP allows multiple nodes to share a set of IP addresses, so if one of the nodes goes down, other nodes can still serve the requests.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD has several unique features related to storage.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Soft updates can protect the consistency of the UFS filesystem (widely used on the BSDs) in the event of a system crash.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Filesystem snapshots allow an image of a UFS filesystem at an instant in time to be efficiently created.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Snapshots allow reliable backup of a live filesystem.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] GEOM is a modular framework that provides RAID (levels 0, 1, 3 currently), full disk encryption, journaling, concatenation, caching, and access to network-backed storage.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] GEOM allows building of complex storage solutions combining ("chaining") these mechanisms.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD provides two frameworks for data encryption: GBDE and Geli.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Both GBDE and Geli operate at the disk level.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] GBDE was written by Poul-Henning Kamp and is distributed under the two-clause BSD license.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Geli is an alternative to GBDE that was written by Pawel Jakub Dawidek and first appeared in FreeBSD 6.0.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] From 7.0 onward, FreeBSD supports the ZFS filesystem.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] ZFS was previously an open-source filesystem that was first developed by Sun Microsystems, but when Oracle acquired Sun, ZFS became a proprietary product.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] However, the FreeBSD project is still developing and improving its ZFS implementation via the OpenZFS project.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The latest stable release of OpenZFS is 2.4.0 which contains numerous improvements, including the addition of a new allocation algorithm, as well as deduplication and block cloning optimizations.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] This version is compatible with FreeBSD releases starting from version 13.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD ships with three different firewall packages: IPFW, pf and IPFilter.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] IPFW is FreeBSD's native firewall. pf was taken from OpenBSD and IPFilter was ported to FreeBSD by Darren Reed.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Taken from OpenBSD, the OpenSSH program was included in the default install.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] OpenSSH is a free implementation of the SSH protocol and is a replacement for telnet.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Unlike telnet, OpenSSH encrypts all information (including usernames and passwords).
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In November 2012, The FreeBSD Security Team announced that hackers gained unauthorized access on two of the project's servers.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] These servers were turned off immediately.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] More research demonstrated that the first unauthorized access by hackers occurred on 19 September.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Apparently hackers gained access to these servers by stealing SSH keys from one of the developers, not by exploiting a bug in the operating system itself.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] These two hacked servers were part of the infrastructure used to build third-party software packages.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The FreeBSD Security Team checked the integrity of the binary packages and determined that no unauthorized changes were made to the binary packages, but stated that it could not guarantee the integrity of packages that were downloaded between 19 September and 11 November.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD provides several security-related features including access-control lists (ACLs), security event auditing, extended file system attributes, mandatory access controls (MAC) and fine-grained capabilities.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] These security enhancements were developed by the **TrustedBSD** project.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The project was founded by Robert Watson with the goal of implementing concepts from the Common Criteria for Information Technology Security Evaluation and the Orange Book.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] This project is ongoing and many of its extensions have been integrated into FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The project has also ported the NSA's FLASK/TE implementation from SELinux to FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Other work includes the development of OpenBSM, an open-source implementation of Sun's Basic Security Module (BSM) API and audit log file format, which supports an extensive security audit system.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] This was shipped as part of FreeBSD 6.2.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Other infrastructure work in FreeBSD performed as part of the TrustedBSD Project has included GEOM and OpenPAM.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Most components of the TrustedBSD project are eventually folded into the main sources for FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In addition, many features, once fully matured, find their way into other operating systems.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] For example, OpenPAM has been adopted by NetBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Moreover, the TrustedBSD MAC Framework has been adopted by Apple for macOS.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD has been ported to a variety of instruction set architectures.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The FreeBSD project organizes architectures into tiers that characterize the level of support provided.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Tier 1 architectures are mature and fully supported, e.g. it is the only tier "supported by the security officer".
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Tier 2 architectures are under active development but are not fully supported.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Tier 3 architectures are experimental or are no longer under active development.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The 32-bit ARM (including OTG) support is mostly aimed at embedded systems (ARM64 is also aimed at servers), but FreeBSD also runs on a number of 32-bit ARM single-board computers, including the BeagleBone Black, Raspberry Pi and Wandboard.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] DEC Alpha, 32-bit little-endian ARMv4/v5/v6, 32-bit big-endian ARM, IA-32, IA-64, 32-bit and 64-bit MIPS, 32-bit PowerPC, 64-bit SPARC, and 64-bit soft-float RISC-V were supported in earlier releases but are not supported in the current release.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Supported devices are listed in the FreeBSD 14.3 Hardware Notes.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The document describes the devices currently known to be supported by FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Other configurations may also work, but simply have not been tested yet.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Rough automatically extracted lists of supported device ids are available in a third party repository.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In 2020, a new project was introduced to automatically collect information about tested hardware configurations.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD has a software repository of over 30,000 applications that are developed by third parties.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Examples include windowing systems, web browsers, email clients, office suites and so forth.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In general, the project itself does not develop this software, only the framework to allow these programs to be installed, which is known as the Ports collection.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Applications may either be compiled from source ("ports"), provided their licensing terms allow this, or downloaded as precompiled binaries ("packages").
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The Ports collection supports the current and stable branches of FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Older releases are not supported and may or may not work correctly with an up-to-date Ports collection.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Ports use Makefiles to automatically fetch the desired application's source code, either from a local or remote repository, unpack it on the system, apply patches to it and compile it.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Depending on the size of the source code, compiling can take a long time, but it gives the user more control over the process and its result.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Most ports also have package counterparts (i.e. precompiled binaries), giving the user a choice.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Although this method is faster, the user has fewer customization options.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD version 10.0 introduced the package manager pkg as a replacement for the previously used package tools.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] It is functionally similar to apt and yum in Linux distributions.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] It allows for installation, upgrading and removal of both ports and packages.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In addition to pkg, PackageKit can also be used to access the Ports collection.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] First introduced in FreeBSD version 4, jails are a security mechanism and an implementation of OS-level virtualization that enables the user to run multiple instances of a guest operating system on top of a FreeBSD host.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] It is an enhanced version of the traditional chroot mechanism.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] A process that runs within such a jail is unable to access the resources outside of it.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Every jail has its own hostname and IP address.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] It is possible to run multiple jails at the same time, but the kernel is shared among all of them.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Hence only software supported by the FreeBSD kernel can be run within a jail.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] bhyve, a new virtualization solution, was introduced in FreeBSD 10.0. bhyve allows a user to run a number of guest operating systems (FreeBSD, OpenBSD, Linux, and Microsoft Windows) simultaneously.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Other operating systems such as Illumos are planned. bhyve was written by Neel Natu and Peter Grehan and was announced in the 2011 BSDCan conference for the first time.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The main difference between bhyve and FreeBSD jails is that jails are an operating system-level virtualization and therefore limited to only FreeBSD guests; but bhyve is a type 2 hypervisor and is not limited to only FreeBSD guests.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] For comparison, bhyve is a similar technology to KVM whereas jails are closer to LXC containers or Solaris Zones.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Since FreeBSD 11.0, there has been support for running as the Dom0 privileged domain for the Xen type 1 hypervisor.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Support for running as DomU (guest) has been available since FreeBSD 8.0.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] VirtualBox (without the closed-source Extension Pack) and QEMU are available on FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Most software that runs on Linux can run on FreeBSD using an optional built-in compatibility layer.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Hence, most Linux binaries can be run on FreeBSD, including some proprietary applications distributed only in binary form.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] This compatibility layer is not an emulation; Linux's system call interface is implemented in the FreeBSD's kernel and hence, Linux executable images and shared libraries are treated the same as FreeBSD's native executable images and shared libraries.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Additionally, FreeBSD provides compatibility layers for several other Unix-like operating systems, in addition to Linux, such as BSD/OS and SVR4, however, it is more common for users to compile those programs directly on FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] No noticeable performance penalty over native FreeBSD programs has been noted when running Linux binaries, and, in some cases, these may even perform more smoothly than on Linux.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] However, the layer is not altogether seamless, and some Linux binaries are unusable or only partially usable on FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] There is support for system calls up to version 4.4.0, available since FreeBSD 14.0.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] As of release 10.3, FreeBSD can run 64-bit Linux binaries.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD has implemented a number of Microsoft Windows native NDIS kernel interfaces to allow FreeBSD to run (otherwise) Windows-only network drivers.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The Wine compatibility layer, which allows the running of software made for Microsoft Windows on Unix-like operating systems, is available for FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD's kernel provides support for some essential tasks such as managing processes, communication, booting and filesystems.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD has a monolithic kernel, with a modular design.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Different parts of the kernel, such as drivers, are designed as modules.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The user can load and unload these modules at any time.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] ULE is the default scheduler in FreeBSD since version 7.1, it supports SMP and SMT.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The FreeBSD kernel has also a scalable event notification interface, named kqueue.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] It has been ported to other BSD-derivatives such as OpenBSD and NetBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Kernel threading was introduced in FreeBSD 5.0, using an M:N threading model.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] This model works well in theory, but it is hard to implement and few operating systems support it.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Although FreeBSD's implementation of this model worked, it did not perform well, so from version 7.0 onward, FreeBSD started using a 1:1 threading model, called libthr.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD's documentation consists of its handbooks, manual pages, mailing list archives, FAQs and a variety of articles, mainly maintained by The FreeBSD Documentation Project.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD's documentation is translated into several languages.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] All official documentation is released under the FreeBSD Documentation License, "a permissive non-copyleft free documentation license that is compatible with the GNU FDL".
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD's documentation is described as "high-quality".
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The FreeBSD project maintains a variety of mailing lists.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Among the most popular mailing lists are FreeBSD-questions (general questions) and FreeBSD-hackers (a place for asking more technical questions).
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Since 2004, the New York City BSD Users Group database provides dmesg information from a collection of computers (laptops, workstations, single-board computers, embedded systems, virtual machines, etc.) running FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] From version 2.0 to 8.4, FreeBSD used the sysinstall program as its main installer.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] It uses a text user interface, and is divided into a number of menus and screens that can be used to configure and control the installation process.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] It can also be used to install Ports and Packages as an alternative to the command-line interface.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The sysinstall utility is now considered deprecated in favor of bsdinstall, a new installer which was introduced in FreeBSD 9.0. bsdinstall is "a lightweight replacement for sysinstall" that was written in sh.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] According to OSNews, "It has lost some features while gaining others, but it is a much more flexible design, and will ultimately be significant improvement".
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Prior to 14.0, the default login shell was tcsh for root and the Almquist shell (sh) for regular users.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Starting with 14.0, the default shell is sh for both root and regular users.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The default scripting shell is the Almquist shell.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD is developed by a volunteer team located around the world.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The developers use the Internet for all communication and many have not met each other in person.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In addition to local user groups sponsored and attended by users, an annual conference, called BSDcon, is held by USENIX.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] BSDcon is not FreeBSD-specific so it deals with the technical aspects of all BSD-derived operating systems, including OpenBSD and NetBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In addition to BSDcon, three other annual conferences, EuroBSDCon, AsiaBSDCon and BSDCan take place in Europe, Japan and Canada respectively.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The FreeBSD Project is run by around 500 committers or developers who have commit access to the master source code repositories and can develop, debug or enhance any part of the system.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Most of the developers are volunteers and few developers are paid by some companies.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] There are several kinds of committers, including source committers (base operating system), doc committers (documentation and website authors) and ports (third-party application porting and infrastructure).
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Every two years the FreeBSD committers select a 9-member FreeBSD Core Team, which is responsible for overall project direction, setting and enforcing project rules and approving new committers, or the granting of commit access to the source code repositories.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] A number of responsibilities are officially assigned to other development teams by the FreeBSD Core Team, for example, responsibility for managing the ports collection is delegated to the Ports Management Team.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In addition to developers, FreeBSD has thousands of "contributors".
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Contributors are also volunteers outside of the FreeBSD project who submit patches for consideration by committers, as they do not have commit access to FreeBSD's source code repository.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Committers then evaluate contributors' submissions and decide what to accept and what to reject.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] A contributor who submits high-quality patches is often asked to become a committer.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD developers maintain at least two branches of simultaneous development.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The *-CURRENT* branch always represents the "bleeding edge" of FreeBSD development.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] A *-STABLE* branch of FreeBSD is created for each major version number, from which -RELEASE is cut about once every 4–6 months.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] If a feature is sufficiently stable and mature it will likely be backported (*MFC* or *Merge from CURRENT* in FreeBSD developer slang) to the *-STABLE* branch.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD development is supported in part by the FreeBSD Foundation.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The foundation is a non-profit organization that accepts donations to fund FreeBSD development.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Such funding has been used to sponsor developers for specific activities, purchase hardware and network infrastructure, provide travel grants to developer summits, and provide legal support to the FreeBSD project.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In November 2014, the FreeBSD Foundation received US$1 million donation from Jan Koum, co-founder and CEO of WhatsApp – the largest single donation to the Foundation since its inception.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In December 2016, Jan Koum donated another $500,000.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Jan Koum himself is a FreeBSD user since the late 1990s and WhatsApp uses FreeBSD on its servers.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD is released under a variety of open-source licenses.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The kernel code and most newly created code are released under the two-clause BSD license which allows everyone to use and redistribute FreeBSD as they wish.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] This license was approved by Free Software Foundation and Open Source Initiative as a Free Software and Open Source license respectively.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Free Software Foundation described this license as "a lax, permissive non-copyleft free software license, compatible with the GNU GPL".
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] There are parts released under three- and four-clause BSD licenses, as well as the Beerware license.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Some device drivers include a binary blob, such as the Atheros HAL of FreeBSD versions before 7.2.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Some of the code contributed by other projects is licensed under GPL, LGPL, CDDL and ISC.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] All the code licensed under GPL and CDDL is clearly separated from the code under liberal licenses, to make it easy for users such as embedded device manufacturers to use only permissive free software licenses.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] ClangBSD aims to replace some GPL dependencies in the FreeBSD base system by replacing the GNU compiler collection with the BSD-licensed LLVM/Clang compiler.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] ClangBSD became self-hosting on 16 April 2010.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] For many years FreeBSD's logo was the generic BSD Daemon, also called *Beastie*, a distorted pronunciation of *BSD*.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] However, Beastie was not unique to FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Beastie first appeared in 1976 on Unix T-shirts of comic artist Phil Foglio art, for Mike O'Brien, with some purchased by Bell Labs.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] More popular versions of the BSD daemon were drawn by animation director John Lasseter beginning in 1984.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Several FreeBSD-specific versions were later drawn by Tatsumi Hosokawa.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] In lithographic terms, the Lasseter graphic is not line art and often requires a screened, four-color photo offset printing process for faithful reproduction on physical surfaces such as paper.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Also, the BSD daemon was thought to be too graphically detailed for smooth size scaling and aesthetically over-dependent on multiple color gradations, making it hard to reliably reproduce as a simple, standardized logo in only two or three colors, much less in monochrome.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Because of these worries, a competition was held and a new logo designed by Anton K.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Gural, still echoing the BSD daemon, was released on 8 October 2005.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] However, it was announced by Robert Watson that the FreeBSD project is "seeking a new logo, but not a new mascot" and that the FreeBSD project would continue to use Beastie as its mascot.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The name "FreeBSD" was coined by David Greenman on 19 June 1993, other suggested names were "BSDFree86" and "Free86BSD".
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] FreeBSD's slogan, "The Power to Serve", is a trademark of The FreeBSD Foundation.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] There are a number of software distributions based on FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] All these distributions have no or only minor changes when compared with the original FreeBSD base system.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] The main difference to the original FreeBSD is that they come with pre-installed and pre-configured software for specific use cases.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] This can be compared with Linux distributions, which are all binary compatible because they use the same kernel and also use the same basic tools, compilers, and libraries while coming with different applications, configurations, and branding.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Besides these distributions, there are some independent operating systems based on FreeBSD.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] DragonFly BSD is a fork from FreeBSD 4.8 aiming for a different multiprocessor synchronization strategy than the one chosen for FreeBSD 5 and development of some microkernel features.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] It does not aim to stay compatible with FreeBSD and has huge differences in the kernel and basic userland.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] MidnightBSD is a fork of FreeBSD 6.1 borrowing heavily from NeXTSTEP, particularly in the user interface department.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Darwin, the core of Apple's macOS, includes a virtual file system and network stack derived from those of FreeBSD, and components of its userspace are also FreeBSD-derived.
[src:freebsd-os/freebsd] Chimera Linux is a desktop Linux distribution with FreeBSD userland.
